To solve this, we first need to eliminate the denominator by multiplying both sides by $(x^2+2x-15)$. This gives us: 
\begin{aligned}4x-12 &= x^{2}+2x-15+2x^{2}+4x-30 \\3x^{2}-6x-27 &= 0.\end{aligned}
We can simplify this by dividing each term by 3: 
\begin{aligned}x^{2}-2x-9 &= 0.\end{aligned}
Using the quadratic formula, we get: 
\begin{aligned}x &= \frac{2\pm\sqrt{4+36}}{2} \\x &= \frac{2\pm\sqrt{40}}{2} \\x &= 1\pm\sqrt{10}.\end{aligned}
We have two solutions: $x_1 = 1+\sqrt{10}$ and $x_2 = 1-\sqrt{10}$. The difference between the two is: 
\begin{aligned}x_1 - x_2 &= 1+\sqrt{10}-1+\sqrt{10} \\&= 2\sqrt{10}.\end{aligned></think> <answer> $2\sqrt{10}$ </answer>

